stocks.description: A leading technology company known for its consumer electronics (iPhone, Mac, iPad), software (iOS, macOS), and services (App Store, Apple Music). Apple’s stock is a cornerstone of large-cap growth portfolios.
news: At WWDC 2025, Apple faced criticism over the underwhelming commercial performance of its Vision Pro headset and delays in its Apple Intelligence AI suite, while legal battles in California and Europe intensified under antitrust and digital markets regulations.

On June 4, Needham downgraded AAPL from “Buy” to “Hold” and withdrew its $225 price target, citing lagging revenue and margin growth compared to peers and heightened regulatory scrutiny of Apple’s “platform tax.”

Earlier in May, DA Davidson raised its target from $230 to $250 (“Buy”), while Scotiabank set a “Market Perform” rating and TD Cowen cut its target from $290 to $275, illustrating divergent views on Apple’s near-term trajectory.

stocks.description: A global leader in software (Windows, Office), cloud services (Azure), and cutting-edge AI research. Microsoft’s stock is a staple in technology-focused and dividend-yielding portfolios.
news: Despite a stretched valuation, Microsoft’s AI-driven growth helped it beat Wall Street’s expectations for fiscal Q3 2025, reinforcing confidence in its expanding cloud and AI businesses.
OV Management LLC increased its MSFT stake by 6.5% during Q4, making Microsoft its third-largest holding, signaling continued institutional confidence in the company’s long-term fundamentals.
Analysts from The Fool highlighted Microsoft as a top “Magnificent Seven” growth stock following its April earnings release, noting sustained momentum in cloud adoption and AI integration.

stocks.description: The parent of Google, specializing in internet search, digital advertising, cloud computing, AI research (DeepMind), and consumer hardware.
news: Barclays warns that an unfavorable remedy in the DOJ antitrust case—potentially forcing a Google Chrome divestiture—could trim Alphabet’s share price by up to 25% in a “black swan” scenario.
With a DOJ decision expected in coming months, investors are weighing the long-term impact of potential structural remedies on Alphabet’s core search and advertising businesses.

A Chinese firm retracted a press release about a new Nvidia-compatible AI chip, highlighting ongoing uncertainty in Alphabet’s hardware and AI accelerator partnerships amid U.S.-China technology tensions.

stocks.description: An electric vehicle and clean energy pioneer, also advancing autonomous driving and robotics. Tesla’s stock is known for volatility tied to product announcements and CEO commentary.
news: A public spat with President Trump over EV tax credits led to a 14% intraday decline in TSLA and a $34 billion drop in Elon Musk’s net worth, though analysts believe it won’t derail Tesla’s long-term robotaxi ambitions.

Tesla is poised to begin its robotaxi service in Austin, Texas—potentially as soon as June 12—with an initial fleet of around ten autonomous Model Y vehicles, a development seen as a major value driver.
After losing roughly 25% year-to-date, Tesla’s diversification into AI and energy solutions is cited by 24/7 Wall St. as a source of strong upside potential through 2030.

stocks.description: Formerly Facebook, Meta is a social media and metaverse company operating Facebook, Instagram, WhatsApp, and Reality Labs VR/AR products.
news: In Q1 2025, Meta posted $42.31 billion in revenue and $6.43 in EPS—both ahead of expectations—and raised its capital expenditure forecast to support AI initiatives.
Shares rallied nearly 4% after news that Meta plans to lean heavily on AI to drive future advertising revenue, underscoring the market’s appetite for its AI strategy.
Meta set its next earnings date for July 30 and forecast Q2 2025 revenue of $42.5 billion–$45.5 billion, reflecting cautious optimism amid macro and regulatory headwinds.

stocks.description: A leader in GPUs and AI accelerators for gaming, data centers, and autonomous systems.
news: NVIDIA is developing the “B30” AI chip tailored to the Chinese market, designed for cluster deployments and compliant with U.S. export controls, with plans to manufacture over one million units this year.
At Computex 2025, NVIDIA unveiled the DGX Spark mini PC (GB10 Grace Blackwell Superchip) and DGX Station workstation (GB300 Blackwell Ultra) for AI developers, in partnership with major OEMs.
After dipping to a 52-week low of $86.62 in April, NVIDIA’s stock rebounded to around $142 following a pause in U.S.–China tariffs and strong Q1 results.
